On June 18th 2017, Charleena Lyles, a pregnant mother of four, was killed by the police in her home, in Seattle, WA. Three of Charleena’s children were home when the shooting occurred. SHE had called the Seattle Police Department to report a burglary. The police officers knew that Charleena suffered from mental health issues and knew that she was a survivor of domestic violence and yet they did nothing to de-escalate the situation when they claimed Charleena brandished a knife. Charleena was a petite woman and her family has argued that the officers should have been able to subdue her with less than deadly force._#charleenalyles_#sayhername_#gameday

#sayhername_Atatiana Jefferson and her eight-year-old nephew were playing video games in her Fort Worth home in the early morning of October 11th. A twenty-eight-year-old pre-med graduate, Jefferson went to the window of her bedroom to investigate noises coming from outside the house. Her decision — made in what should have been the security of her own home—would be her last. Outside her window was a man, wearing blue, empowered to take her life on the grounds that he felt threatened by a shadow in the window. 
 
Minutes earlier, her neighbor James Smith had noticed that the front door of Jefferson’s house was open. On an otherwise placid Saturday night, Smith was concerned about the safety of the Jefferson household so he decided to call the non-emergency line of his local police station to request a wellness check: “[There was no] domestic violence, no arguing, nothing that they should have been concerned about as far as them coming with guns drawn to my neighbor’s house,” said Smith. 
 
The Fort Worth police that arrived on-scene concealed their presence and entered Jefferson’s property without warning, as if they were investigating a crime-in-progress. 
 
The officer shouted, “Put your hands up! Show me your hands!” Almost immediately, he fired a single shot into Jefferson’s window. The video cuts. Minutes later, Atatiana Jefferson was pronounced dead. We will not forget. 
 
#sayhername_#atatianajefferson_#gameday_#happybirthdaytome

On February 12, 2013, police were called to Kayla’s Shattuck Avenue apartment by a friend who was concerned about her mental health. Police arrived and immediately attempted to place her under arrest. Kayla was an African American, transgender woman living with schizophrenia. When officers wrestled her face down onto a futon on the floor, they should have known that this could impair her breathing. Up to six cops, using their full weight continued to restrain the panicked woman and even called for a “spit hood” to be placed on her head. Ultimately, they didn’t get a chance use it. They thought she had calmed down; in fact, she had stopped breathing._#kaylamoore_#transblacklivesmattertoo_#sayhername_#gameday

#sayhername_On February 21, 2016 California police officers shot and killed 31-year-old Kisha Michael and her friend Marquintan Sandlin, 32, after initially finding them unconscious and sitting in a stopped car on Manchester Boulevard. Michael was shot 13 times and pronounced dead at the scene, while Sandlin, the driver, was shot eight times and pronounced dead a short time later at a nearby hospital. An autopsy recovered projectiles from at least two and as many as three different types of firearms–a shotgun, handgun and possibly a rifle–from Michael’s body. Grimes says witnesses reported that police fired as many as 100 shots at the pair in the car.

#sayhername_On May 16, 2003, 57 year old Alberta Spruill was getting ready for work when New York police officers performed a “no knock” raid at her home. Officers broke down her door and launched a concussion grenade into her home. After handcuffing Spruill, officers realized that they were in the wrong place and had been misinformed about guns and drugs being in the apartment. Less than two hours later, Spruill passed away from a heart attack. No charges were ever filed._#albertaspruill_#sayhername_#gameday

I’m grateful for all parts of the journey. I’m just having fun! #wnba #HaveFunPlayHard #letgoletgod

Link in bio! Blown away at @britnidlc phenomenal story telling skills. It’s one thing to have your story told and another to have it done by someone with such care, nuance and flat out skill. This is why we need people in positions who represent the communities they’re actually reporting on. Britni is a non binary writer who, in our conversations expanded my language and understanding around marginalized gender identities. It’s important to go beyond pointing out the obvious sports binary and how currently bodies are policed to squeeze people into rigid constructions of gender. How dope would it be if we started to have intentional conversations around how to create healthier, safer, more inclusive environments in sports for those of us who don’t fit the mold? Seems simple enough to me. That is unless people want us to shut up and not exist __. __ :@ruffdraft

I am so incredibly proud of your growth not only as a player, but more so as the phenomenal person you are. You and all the other amazing women you’re surrounded by are pioneers for putting softball back on the map (where it should be).

Representation for not only women, but for the young minority girls who will dream to be the next Lele Ocasio, the same as you dreamed to be the next_@natashawatley29_. I love you the mostest and can’t wait for what the future holds for you and this sport______#BetOnWomen_#SoftballWife_#DatJustMyBabyMama

Poverty is a punishment in so many more ways that I realized. I was shocked to learn 1 in 3 parents worry they won’t have enough money to afford period products for their daughters. No period products means no school and no sports. Both are so important, and create essential and positive opportunities for young women. Being a girl and having a period should never be a reason not to play. Ever. Join the_#SupportedAlways_Instagram Live sessions happening every Wednesday from August 12 – September 30, 2020 to help girls continue to stay involved (even if virtually) in the activities they love. For everyone who joins a session,_@always_brand_will donate a month’s supply of period products, up to a half a million products, via_@womenssportsfoundation_, which is helping girls stay active all over the country and help_#endperiodpoverty.

FBF-August 14,2019 I had my first surgery, and June 15, 2020 was the second. Today is the one year anniversary and I’m still on this scooter. Am I bitter? No!!!! I am grateful. Grateful for all the opportunities I have had because of this and all the people I have been able to connect with. It’s truly a blessing. And more importantly this moment in time, is BIGGER than ME! And I don’t question Gods timing! Thank you to everyone that checks on me on a daily and makes sure I’m good because it was hard!!!!! But when you reflect and you see the bigger picture you realize things are happening FOR you, not TO you! Life is GOOD! #sayhername #positivevibes #keepgoing #stayencouraged

I’m thrilled to announce I’m partnering with_@CapitalOneCafe. This partnership is about so much more than finance and banking, it’s about life. And let me tell you…between moving back home to the Chicagoland area, balancing Lailaa being part-time at-home-school and part-time in-person school, and everything this past year has thrown into our lives, life is crazy. But I know I’m not the only one. We’re all going through something and I know how scary life can sometimes be, but it’s important that we talk about it._ So that’s exactly what I’m going to be doing with Capital One Café. We created a new online experience – featuring yours truly – and we’ll be talking about everything from our values, to relationships, to creating balance and how it all intersects with money._@CapitalOne_is reimagining banking by truly helping people, fostering well-being, and supporting across so many facets. To my beautiful wife to be __

One year ago I asked you to spend forever with me and one year ago you said YES! With all of our people there I couldn’t have asked for a more magical night _

@dming24 you are my person and you have been for so many years. I thank God our paths continued to cross over and over and over again until they eventually united as one. You truly are my better half. I learn daily from you and am inspired by you even more than you know. My heart is truly yours and only yours until the end of time. As you say “you’re stuck with me” __

Even though 2020 hasn’t been the year anyone has anticipated, there is hope and promise in knowing that we are one year closer to forever. I love you with all of me and just know that I ALWAYS got you! __

I love you. I love you. I love you. And I can’t wait to marry you ____

I’d like to analyze some problems of young athletes__
Today’s topic is stress and anxiety on games. I get a lot of DM’s about it and realize this is a major problem__

Being nervous is normal, both young, and professional athletes experience it. Stress appears out of fear of making a mistake, but, in fact, EVERYONE makes mistakes_
When you go out on the court, the main thing is to understand that even if you make a mistake and don’t do what you had to do, it’s not the end of the world.

Even the most famous athletes make mistakes, and it is normal! As soon as you let go of yourself and start enjoying the game, the anxiety will go away.
Trust me, you can do anything_

Tell me, what else bothers you?

I wasn’t going to accept this challenge. But then, I learned the intentions behind it. There are innocent women being killed in Turkey, “honor killings”. Women being murdered for bringing “dishonor” to their families, religion, communities. When a woman is killed, their picture is in the newspaper the next day- a black and white photo. 
 
The second picture is Pinar Gültekin, a 27 year old Turkish women who recently lost her life at the hands of a premeditated murderer. Her death has sparked urgency; urgency toward the Turkish government to protect women and prevent the government from taking away protections against domestic violence and cruel, abusive acts toward women. Her death has been the final straw for Turkish women’s rights activists, and hopefully for all of us. 
 
This challenge is a protest. It is standing with these innocent Turkish women. It is showing united urgency to make sure no more women/people are unjustifiably harmed/killed ever again. Women empower women, human beings empower human bei#ngs, always._#ChallengeAccepted_#Together

August 14th, 2014. Michelle Cusseaux. 50 years old. Killed in her own home by the Phoenix police when they were called for a mental health wellness check. Her mother, “Momma Fran” is known as the godmother of the Say Her Name movement. She brought her daughter’s casket to city hall in downtown Phoenix because she refused to let her daughter die in vain. She made sure Michelle’s name was HEARD- and we are listening. And we, too, are saying her name: MICHELLE CUSSEAUX. 
 
Join us and _@AAPolicyForum_in honoring Michelle and supporting the fight for justice: _https://aapf.org/sayhername

Let me take a moment from where I sit. This is the place I would be before school, after school, before games, during football games, on weekends, with others, alone. I returned here whenever I was home from college. I have returned here after each pro season. In between overseas and the W- I return. I have leaned against this wall for years- dreaming of the moments I am living in. I have cried in here. Thrown the ball across the gym in frustration. Listened to countless Jbiebs albums. I have been built in here. There’s something special about the journey always leading you back to where you have come from- a moment of gratitude, a chance to look back to see how far you have traveled. A place that grounds me and fills me, reminding me we are really out here living what that young Swiese worked for. Allow me to take a moment to recognize her because she deserves that. And let me praise God for the path only He could carve out because He deserves that more. #ThanksForReadingMyMondayNovel #PeaceAndLerv
